SIMPLE: sarcophagus
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sarcophagus
<hw>Sar*coph"a*gus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
L. <plw>Sarcophagi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Sarcophaguses</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>sarkofa`gos</grk>, properly,
eating flesh; <grk>sa`rx</grk>, <grk>sa`rkos</grk>, flesh +
<grk>fagei^n</grk> to eat. Cf. <er>Sarcasm</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A species of limestone used among the Greeks for making coffins,
which was so called because it consumed within a few weeks the flesh of
bodies deposited in it. It is otherwise called <altname>lapis
Assius</altname>, or <altname>Assian stone</altname>, and is said to
have been found at Assos, a city of Lycia.</def>
<rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A coffin or chest-shaped tomb of the kind of stone
described above; hence, any stone coffin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A stone shaped like a sarcophagus and placed by a
grave as a memorial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sarcophagy</ent>⟦br⟧
